To identify the origin of afterglow emission, photophysical properties of the BNDs@B2O3 in powder and suspension were investigated. Fig. 3c shows that the RTP emission of BNDs@B2O3 powder is located at 450 nm, which is gradually red-shifted to 500 nm with the increase of excitation wavelength. The excitation-dependent behavior of RTP emission should be derived from the existence of multiple triplet-excited states in BNDs@B2O3 
                     [4,19]. Under illuminated by the optimal excitation wavelength of 280 nm, the fluorescence and RTP emission of BNDs@B2O3 powder peaked at 430 and 450 nm (Fig. 3d), respectively. The difference of their emission wavelengths further confirms the phosphorescence nature but not fluorescent relaxation. The fluorescence and RTP emission spectra (Fig. 3d) of BNDs@B2O3 powder reveal the 20 nm Stokes shifts between fluorescence and RTP under the excitation of 280 nm at room temperature. The calculated energy gap (ΔEST
                     ) between the lowest singlet state (S1
                     ) and triplet state (T1
                     ) is as small as 0.13 eV, facilitating the effective ISC [44]. In addition, the fluorescence emission of BNDs@B2O3 powder is also excitation-dependent due to the multiple singlet excited states (Figure S10) [19]. The excitation-dependent behavior is mainly attributed to the formation of multiple emisison centers based on different surface functional groups, defect sites and size difference of BNDs. The absorption, fluorescence and RTP excitation spectra of BNDs@B2O3 powders were also studied (Figure S11). The absorption and fluorescence excitation peaks partially overlap at ~ 330 nm, which is attributed to electron transition of C-containing fluorescent groups. The absorption and RTP excitation peaks patially overlap at ~ 280 nm., which is derived from defect formation due to the doping of C and O atoms in BND. However, because the optimal excitation wavelengths of fluorescence and phosphorescence are 330 and 280 nm, the fluorescence and phosphorescence emission features are mainly attributed to the carbon-doping and defect effects, respectively. The defects in BNDs can generate deep electronic levels lying below the conduction band, which determines the formation of luminescence center. In addition, C-related defects (such as C-N group) in BN can also enhance the spin–orbit coupling, improve the ISC efficiency, and further promote the population of triplet excited electrons, which provides a guarantee for RTP emission. Furthermore, the time-resolved RTP decay spectrum of the BNDs@B2O3 powder was measured (Fig. 3e). The curve can be fitted by a bi-exponential function with two lifetime components: 501.8 ms (40.34%) and 1917.2 ms (59.66%), respectively, implying two decay channels in the RTP attenuation [4,5]. According to the equation for calculating lifetime [45], the average lifetime was as long as 1.704 s (Table S1), which is dominantly longer than most reported CD-based RTP materials (Table S2). The RTP QY of BNDs@B2O3 powder is determined to be 15.9%, which is higher than most of reported state-of-the-art RTP materials (Table S3). Although the QY of our sample is lower than some materials in Table S3, ultralong RTP lifetime of our sample is also worth to be focused. A trade-off between RTP lifetime and quantum yield is significant for superior RTP materials. In addition, the effect of BA content for the RTP lifetime was also investigated. As shown in Fig. 3f, the best phosphorescence performance was achieved when the mass ratio of BA to melamine is 4–6. The mass ratio of BA to melamine less than 4 or more than 6 all degrades their RTP lifetime. Relative shortage of BA possibly led to the phosphorescent oxygen quench, presumably owing to the incomplete protection of BNDs by the B2O3 “outerwear”. Whereas, an excess of BA possibly caused the “outerwear” too chick to extract phosphorescence of BNDs@B2O3 powder.
